items.title: Wurmbea dioica
items.content_text: This particular one was really pink (not sure if the photo on the phone shows it), not the usual purple colour

items.title: Milvus migrans
items.content_text: These two, a whistling kite and a raven where doing acrobatics for about an hour in the morning with each other. Amazing to watch

items.title: Microseris spp., Triodia scariosa
items.content_text: A heap of Microseris coming up amongst the spinifex post burn.

items.title: Arthropodium strictum s.l., Microlaena spp.
items.content_text: This site has extreme grazing pressure from rabbits, wombats and kangaroos. Most plants are eaten unless hidden under logs or other hard to reach places.

items.title: Australoplana alba/sanguinea alba, Australoplana spp.
items.content_text: I think it is Australoplana sanguinea, but not sure. Found beneath a log amongst a Microlaena patch.

items.title: Thinornis rubricollis
items.content_text: Presumably nesting on the main surf beach (didn't want to get too close). There are leg bands on one of them, I sent a clearer photo to Birdlife for their records.

items.title: Neosparassus diana
items.content_text: Note the red mites on the spider

items.title: Callocephalon fimbriatum
items.content_text: Saw about 30 Gang-gang Cockatoos flying from the north to the south. Suprised to see so many this close to home away from large intact vegetation.

items.title: Cynara cardunculus subsp. flavescens, Toxidia doubledayi
Exocarpos cupressiformis, Pachycephala pectoralis
items.content_text: Female with a Exocarpos seed in her mouth.

items.title: Zosterops lateralis
items.content_text: Was collected sheeps wool for a nest

items.title: Platycercus eximius
items.content_text: Poor photo, not much light left. Will upgrade when I get a better shot!
